</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Continuous ambulatory peritoneal dialysis (CAPD) is used to treat end-stage renal failure in an increasing number of patients. CAPD has an advantage over hemodialysis in that it allows patients greater freedom to perform daily activities; it also provides other clinical benefits. However, the long-term effectiveness of CAPD is limited by complications, which have various causes. Complications with an infectious cause include bacterial peritonitis, tuberculous peritonitis, and infections of the catheter exit site and tunnel. Noninfectious complications include catheter dysfunction, dialysate leakage, hernias, and sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis. Many imaging modalities—radiography, ultrasonography, peritoneal scintigraphy, computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance (MR) imaging—are useful for characterizing these complications. CT peritoneography and MR peritoneography are techniques specifically suited to this purpose. Imaging plays a critical role in ensuring that complications are detected early and managed appropriately.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.292085136">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.292085136">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g01x.jpeg" height="1384" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Axial image from CT peritoneography shows a normal distribution of dialysate and contrast medium throughout the peritoneal cavity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g02a.jpeg" height="1559" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Infected fluid collections. <b>(2a)</b> Oblique axial CT image, obtained with intravenous and oral contrast media in a 56-year-old man with fever and abdominal pain, shows gas bubbles and variable attenuation (arrow) in an anterior dialysate collection. <b>(2b)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image shows the heterogeneous appearance of purulent fluid, with coarse echogenic strands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g02b.jpeg" height="1710" width="1707" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Infected fluid collections. <b>(2a)</b> Oblique axial CT image, obtained with intravenous and oral contrast media in a 56-year-old man with fever and abdominal pain, shows gas bubbles and variable attenuation (arrow) in an anterior dialysate collection. <b>(2b)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image shows the heterogeneous appearance of purulent fluid, with coarse echogenic strands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g03x.jpeg" height="1574" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3.</b>  Infected fluid collections. Transverse gray-scale US image obtained in a 31-year-old man shows a largely anechoic focus with an internal network of coarse echogenic fibrous strands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g04x.jpeg" height="1433" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4.</b>  Tuberculous peritonitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thickened and matted appearance of the bowel wall and peritoneal enhancement in a 71-year-old man.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g05x.jpeg" height="1178" width="1404" aria-labelledby="F5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5.</b>  Tuberculous peritonitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows ascites and mild peritoneal enhancement in a 70-year-old man with polycystic kidney disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g06x.jpeg" height="1717" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6.</b>  US appearances of normal and infected catheter sites. Oblique sagittal gray-scale image shows parallel hyperechoic lines indicative of a normal catheter tunnel, with the typical deep acoustic shadow beneath the cuff.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g07x.jpeg" height="1715" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7.</b>  US appearances of normal and infected catheter sites. Oblique transverse gray-scale image obtained in a 64-year-old woman with abdominal pain shows anechoic areas around the catheter, findings indicative of a fluid collection in the infected tunnel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g08x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1427" aria-labelledby="F8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8.</b>  Diagram shows the correct placement of a straight Tenckhoff catheter for CAPD, with the tip pointing downward in the pelvis. Superficial and deep cuffs are designed to keep the catheter anchored in the proper position. (Courtesy of Justin Harris, MBBS, Department of Radiology, Royal Free Hospital, London, England.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g09a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1231" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  <b>(a)</b> Abdominal radiograph obtained in a 24-year-old man shows the correct position of a CAPD catheter, with the tip in the pelvis. The surgical clips are from a previous failed renal transplant. <b>(b)</b> Abdominal radiograph obtained in the same patient 4 weeks later shows malposition of the CAPD catheter tip in the right flank.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g09b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1230" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  <b>(a)</b> Abdominal radiograph obtained in a 24-year-old man shows the correct position of a CAPD catheter, with the tip in the pelvis. The surgical clips are from a previous failed renal transplant. <b>(b)</b> Abdominal radiograph obtained in the same patient 4 weeks later shows malposition of the CAPD catheter tip in the right flank.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g10x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1441" aria-labelledby="F10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10.</b>  Abdominal radiograph shows a kink in the intraperitoneal portion of the CAPD catheter.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g11x.jpeg" height="1332" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11.</b>  Catheter entrapment. Axial image from CT peritoneography, obtained because of poor drainage of dialysate during CAPD, shows entrapment of the catheter tip in the mesentery. The catheter was removed and a new one was surgically implanted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g12x.jpeg" height="1372" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12.</b>  Axial T2-weighted MR image shows the low-signal-intensity CAPD catheter (arrow) with its tip trapped in an isolated locule of high-signal-intensity dialysate (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g13x.jpeg" height="1214" width="1530" aria-labelledby="F13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13.</b>  Axial image from CT peritoneography in a 64-year-old woman with end-stage renal failure secondary to adult polycystic kidney disease shows a dialysate leak in the anterior abdominal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g14x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1391" aria-labelledby="F14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14.</b>  Coronal T2-weighted MR image obtained in a 59-year-old man undergoing CAPD shows a right-sided anterior abdominal wall leak and, in the right side of the scrotum, a hydrocele containing high-signal-intensity dialysate.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g15a.jpeg" height="1528" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Hiatal hernia in a 58-year-old woman undergoing CAPD. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> images from CT peritoneography show a small sliding hiatal hernia that contains enhancing dialysate (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g15b.jpeg" height="1672" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Hiatal hernia in a 58-year-old woman undergoing CAPD. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> images from CT peritoneography show a small sliding hiatal hernia that contains enhancing dialysate (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g16x.jpeg" height="1512" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16.</b>  Hernia in a 61-year-old man undergoing CAPD. Axial CT image shows a periumbilical hernia that contains dialysate.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g17a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1764" aria-labelledby="F17A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17a.</b>  Peritoneal scintigrams show hydrothorax as a complication of CAPD in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Scintigram obtained with the patient supine, 2 hours after an intraperitoneal injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc sulfur colloid, shows normal distribution of the radionuclide within the peritoneum, without passage to the pleural space. <b>(b, c)</b> Delayed scintigrams obtained 19 hours later show free movement of the radionuclide through the pleural space, with accumulation in a supradiaphragmatic location when the patient is supine (arrow in <b>b</b>) and in a dependent location when the patient is upright (<b>c</b>). (Case courtesy of Eric Goffin, MD, Department of Nephrology, Université Catholique de Louvain, Brussels, Belgium.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F17A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g17b.jpeg" height="1422" width="1343" aria-labelledby="F17B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17b.</b>  Peritoneal scintigrams show hydrothorax as a complication of CAPD in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Scintigram obtained with the patient supine, 2 hours after an intraperitoneal injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc sulfur colloid, shows normal distribution of the radionuclide within the peritoneum, without passage to the pleural space. <b>(b, c)</b> Delayed scintigrams obtained 19 hours later show free movement of the radionuclide through the pleural space, with accumulation in a supradiaphragmatic location when the patient is supine (arrow in <b>b</b>) and in a dependent location when the patient is upright (<b>c</b>). (Case courtesy of Eric Goffin, MD, Department of Nephrology, Université Catholique de Louvain, Brussels, Belgium.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F17B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g17c.jpeg" height="1332" width="1222" aria-labelledby="F17C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17c.</b>  Peritoneal scintigrams show hydrothorax as a complication of CAPD in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Scintigram obtained with the patient supine, 2 hours after an intraperitoneal injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc sulfur colloid, shows normal distribution of the radionuclide within the peritoneum, without passage to the pleural space. <b>(b, c)</b> Delayed scintigrams obtained 19 hours later show free movement of the radionuclide through the pleural space, with accumulation in a supradiaphragmatic location when the patient is supine (arrow in <b>b</b>) and in a dependent location when the patient is upright (<b>c</b>). (Case courtesy of Eric Goffin, MD, Department of Nephrology, Université Catholique de Louvain, Brussels, Belgium.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F17C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g18x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1452" aria-labelledby="F18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis in a 26-year-old woman undergoing CAPD. Abdominal radiograph shows bowel wall calcification and a mal-positioned CAPD catheter with its tip overlying the left ilium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g19x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1651" aria-labelledby="F19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19.</b>  Barium follow-through study in a 22-year-old man with abdominal pain while undergoing CAPD shows central fixation and dilatation of small-bowel loops with thickening of the bowel wall. Transit time of the contrast medium was slower than normal. These findings were suggestive of sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g20a.jpeg" height="1645" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20a.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis (same patient as in <a href="#F19">Fig 19</a>). <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image depicts a peritoneal fluid collection with the appearance of internal septa. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows the same fluid collection with several highly attenuating foci indicative of early peritoneal calcification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F20A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g20b.jpeg" height="1471" width="1637" aria-labelledby="F20B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20b.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis (same patient as in <a href="#F19">Fig 19</a>). <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image depicts a peritoneal fluid collection with the appearance of internal septa. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows the same fluid collection with several highly attenuating foci indicative of early peritoneal calcification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F20B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g21x.jpeg" height="1548" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21.</b>  Axial CT image shows advanced peritoneal calcification in a 34-year-old woman with sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g22a.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22a.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(22)</b> Axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and gray-scale US image <b>(b)</b> show large linear foci of peritoneal calcification in a 68-year-old woman.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F22A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g22b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1782" aria-labelledby="F22B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22b.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(22)</b> Axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and gray-scale US image <b>(b)</b> show large linear foci of peritoneal calcification in a 68-year-old woman.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F22B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g23a.jpeg" height="1276" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23a.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(23)</b> Axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and gray-scale US image <b>(b)</b> show a loculated fluid collection in the pelvis of a 26-year-old woman with abdominal pain and bloody dialysate effluent. Foci of peritoneal calcification also are visible in <b>a</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F23A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g23b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1743" aria-labelledby="F23B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23b.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(23)</b> Axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and gray-scale US image <b>(b)</b> show a loculated fluid collection in the pelvis of a 26-year-old woman with abdominal pain and bloody dialysate effluent. Foci of peritoneal calcification also are visible in <b>a</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F23B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g24x.jpeg" height="1468" width="1692" aria-labelledby="F24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(24)</b> Axial CT image shows extensive calcification of the bowel wall and peritoneum in a 34-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#F21">Fig 21</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g25x.jpeg" height="1401" width="1638" aria-labelledby="F25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(25)</b> Axial CT image shows bowel wall thickening in a 56-year-old woman.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g26a.jpeg" height="1364" width="1656" aria-labelledby="F26A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26a.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(26a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 63-year-old woman shows a loculated fluid collection and desmoplastic reaction of the mesentery. <b>(26b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 6 months later shows increased size of the collection and progression of the desmoplastic reaction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F26A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g26b.jpeg" height="1395" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F26B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26b.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(26a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 63-year-old woman shows a loculated fluid collection and desmoplastic reaction of the mesentery. <b>(26b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 6 months later shows increased size of the collection and progression of the desmoplastic reaction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F26B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g27a.jpeg" height="1485" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F27A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27a.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(27a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 65-year-old man shows a normal distribution of dialysate in the abdomen. <b>(27b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 18 months later shows a large fluid collection in the anterior part of the abdomen with some early tethering of small-bowel loops posterior to the collection. <b>(27c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 9 months after <b>27b</b> shows the collection, which is highly attenuating and loculated, with septa of slightly higher attenuation now visible. Increased tethering and wall thickening of the posterior small-bowel loops and marked thickening of the peritoneum also are depicted. <b>(27d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the complexity of the collection, with loculated fluid of mixed echogenicity (arrow) adjacent to loculated anechoic fluid (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F27A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g27b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F27B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27b.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(27a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 65-year-old man shows a normal distribution of dialysate in the abdomen. <b>(27b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 18 months later shows a large fluid collection in the anterior part of the abdomen with some early tethering of small-bowel loops posterior to the collection. <b>(27c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 9 months after <b>27b</b> shows the collection, which is highly attenuating and loculated, with septa of slightly higher attenuation now visible. Increased tethering and wall thickening of the posterior small-bowel loops and marked thickening of the peritoneum also are depicted. <b>(27d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the complexity of the collection, with loculated fluid of mixed echogenicity (arrow) adjacent to loculated anechoic fluid (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F27B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g27c.jpeg" height="1369" width="1566" aria-labelledby="F27C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27c.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(27a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 65-year-old man shows a normal distribution of dialysate in the abdomen. <b>(27b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 18 months later shows a large fluid collection in the anterior part of the abdomen with some early tethering of small-bowel loops posterior to the collection. <b>(27c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 9 months after <b>27b</b> shows the collection, which is highly attenuating and loculated, with septa of slightly higher attenuation now visible. Increased tethering and wall thickening of the posterior small-bowel loops and marked thickening of the peritoneum also are depicted. <b>(27d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the complexity of the collection, with loculated fluid of mixed echogenicity (arrow) adjacent to loculated anechoic fluid (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F27C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g27d.jpeg" height="1574" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F27D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27d.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis as a complication of CAPD. <b>(27a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a 65-year-old man shows a normal distribution of dialysate in the abdomen. <b>(27b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 18 months later shows a large fluid collection in the anterior part of the abdomen with some early tethering of small-bowel loops posterior to the collection. <b>(27c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 9 months after <b>27b</b> shows the collection, which is highly attenuating and loculated, with septa of slightly higher attenuation now visible. Increased tethering and wall thickening of the posterior small-bowel loops and marked thickening of the peritoneum also are depicted. <b>(27d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the complexity of the collection, with loculated fluid of mixed echogenicity (arrow) adjacent to loculated anechoic fluid (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F27D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F28" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085136/asset/images/g09mr14g28x.jpeg" height="1400" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 28.</b>  Hepatic subcapsular steatosis in a 52-year-old diabetic man undergoing intraperitoneal insulin therapy with CAPD. Axial CT image shows subcapsular areas of low attenuation that create a vaguely scalloped appearance along the periphery of the liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085136&amp;id=F28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section